<font color="#FF0000">PLF'S AND OTHER STUFF</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 17  1:11:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Just surfaced a few minutes ago.  The water's pretty mucked up here, so I haven't seen a lot.  It's hard to feel dirty after you've been under, but if you play in dirty water, well you get the drift.<br><br>
Tips for doing PLF's:<br><br>
1.  Be sure to wear the parachute, and strap the leg straps down tight.  If they aren't tight, they can slide up a bet, and catch something which will make you forget all about landing.  Same, same if you decide to cross them when fitting the harness.  <br><br>
2.  Always look at the horizon, not the ground.  If you look at the ground, you might get an idea of where, exactly, you will land and sametimes you really don't want to know.<br><br>
3.  Try keeping your legs together--if they are not, a limb or something could catch you (refer to #1 above).<br><br>
4.  Most everyone, excepting Cookie, should put their arms over their face.  After all, if something's going to break, it's better that it be out of sight.  But for Marines, scars make them look better.<br><br>
5.  Be sure to hit on the balls of your feet, and roll to the soft parts (except for Cookie, who has no soft parts).  That's the calf, thigh, butt, and shoulder.<br><br>
6.  Tuck your head!  (Refer to #4 above.)  <br><br>
7.  Release your riser on one side so that you won't be dragged through briers, thorns, ditches, off cliffs (except for Cookie, who enjoys the second header off the cliff and lands on his feet to show off a bit), etc.  <br><br>
8.  Relax and enjoy the sights from flat on your back.  While you are at it, see if everything still works right (toes, feet, legs, arms, back, head).  <br><br>
9.  Sit up and look around.  Were there any girls watching?  If so, get up and start gathering up the parachute in a non-chalant manner.  If not, start screaming at the guy who pushed you out of the plane in the first place.<br><br>
10.  See if there's a way out other than walking.<br><br>
That's how to do a parachute landing fall (PLF).  Of course, there's another type of landing, called a PFL or &quot;poor fouled-up (you can use the other word too) landing.  This is the one's that most pilots do, and it consists of breaking any of the above rules.  Usually, if someone decides to break one, he then breaks them all, and sometimes breaks other things as well.<br><br>
Well, time to put on a fresh scuba tank and jump in the river again.  Enjoy!<br><br>
Ed, 'really appreciated your thoughts about how to say &quot;Thanks&quot; to all those guys who were on the ground.  I sometimes felt we who flew had things pretty easy until the **** hit the fan.  But day-to-day, those ground pounders really worked and did the rough stuff.  THANKS fellows.  We won't forget.
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


